load libraries

Using the developer version of tigris for grabbing 2020 block shapefiles correctly.

Grab population and block data for 2020

The city I choosed is Redwood City, which is the county seat in San Mateo (081), California (06)
The variable name of total population in 2020 is ‘P1_001N’ 2020 population data: smc_pop_2020 2020 block data: blocks_2020

Grab population and block data for 2010

The variable name of total population in 2010 is ‘P001001’ 2010 population data: smc_pop_2010 2010 block data: blocks_2010

Construct aligned geometry

  • Get the blocks (2010) within Redwood City’s boundary: place_blocks_2010
  • head(place_blocks_2010)

Observation and Analysis

  • In this report, I use the third method in spatial subsetting descripted in Chapter 2.4. We need a hypothesis here. That is “The population is evenly distributed in the blocks”. Obviously, this assumption is different from reality. However, under the known data, considering that the blocks in 2020 have changed compared with those in 2010, this method can be used as a more reasonable choice.

  • In the past ten years, the total population of the city has shown an increasing trend. A total of 7453 people has increased in the city in the past ten years. However, population density growth / migration is mainly concentrated in a few blocks. For most blocks, the change of population density is not obvious. This trend can be seen easily from the second figure whose color palette is symmetrical across 0. Because most blocks in Redwood City are white, which means no population increased or decreased in the ten years.

  • Total population change:

## [1] 7453
  • The population density loss in some blocks is obvious, which needs special attention, such as 060816103042020, 060816102021046, 060816103021043 and 060816107001017. The four blocks lost more than 100 people per acre in the past ten years.

  • There are many possible reasons for the increase or decrease of population density. For example, the re planning and construction of the block, the change of infrastructure near the block, and the basic situation of the original population of the block (such as the age composition of the population). The specific reasons for the increase and decrease of population density in the above blocks need further research.
